 marginalises them is not. This is demonstrated by comparing their position to that of other marginalised minorities around the globe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMarginality, SocialzEurope. 0aRomaniesxLegal status, laws, etczEurope. 0aRomaniesxLegal status, laws, etc.zEurope. 0aRomaniesxSegregationzEurope. 0aRomanieszEuropexSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General.2bisacsh  aEurope.  aRoma.  aStatelessness.  acitizenship.  adiscrimination.  aethnicity.  ahuman rights.  amigration.  aminority rights.  aracism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packagez978311128198840uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526143136zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526143136zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526143136/original  a978-3-11-128198-8 Manchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packageb2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA